The paper deals with fundamental problems in distributed computing, specifically Byzantine broadcast and agreement, which are typically studied in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses communication complexity, which is a common topic in the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) and Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper presents new protocols with improved efficiency, which could fall under the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses asynchronous reliable broadcast, which could be relevant to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
